@ThinkingandTinkering If the feathers flex more than the turbine blades there may be some gain due to variable geometry, especially with respect to the Darwin collector, which produces uneven airspeed over the area of the turbine.
Also the feathers not currently being blown on may rotate on the hinge producing less air resistance, implying that turning the concept of the feather turbine upside down may produce a better effect.
Sorry for the rambling reply, MY fizzing brain thought of the second part while writing the first.
